    "summary": "KEEP \"impels\" — different Chinese, different motivational stage",
    "content": "**KEEP \"impels\"** in footnote [^3].\n\nThe Chinese is doing different things in the two places:\n\n- **Body text**: 使得我想要去 — \"makes me *want to*.\" This is about the emergence of a desire, a motivational state. \"Moves me to want to\" correctly captures the softer, desire-forming quality.\n\n- **Footnote [^3]**: 使得（推动）我去做 — \"makes (pushes/drives) me to *do*.\" The author parenthetically glosses 使得 with 推动 (push/drive), explicitly strengthening the verb. And the target is action (做), not desire (想要). This is about force toward behavior, not the formation of a want.\n\nFrom a philosophy-of-mind perspective, these are two distinct stages of the motivational chain: (1) feeling generates desire (body text — wanting), (2) desire generates action (footnote — doing). The first is weaker, the second stronger. The author marks this difference deliberately with 想要 vs 推动. \"Moves\" vs \"impels\" correctly mirrors this gradient.\n\nHarmonizing would erase a real philosophical distinction in the original."
  }
